e of war: Refreshing epic and reworking Homer in Flavian poetry -- tEpic on the edge: generic instability at the pivotal centre of Silius’ Punica (10.336‒371) -- tSilius, Sicily, and the poetics of generic conflict: Grosphus in Punica 14.208‒217 -- tLyric resonances in Statius’ Achilleid -- tVII. Epic and Other Genres -- tBurial scenes: Silius Italicus’ Punica and Greco-Roman historiography -- tIs Capaneus an Epicurean? A case study in epic and philosophy -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe construction of a new Latin library between the end of the Republic and the Augustan Principate was anything but an inhibiting factor. The literary flourishing of the Flavian age shows that awareness of this canon rather stimulated creative tension. In the changing socio-cultural context, daring innovations transform the genres of poetry and prose. This volume, which collects papers by influential scholars of early Imperial literature, sheds light on the productive dynamics of the ancient genre system and can also offer insightful perspectives to a non-classicist readership.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aFlavian Age. 0aLatin literaturexHistory and criticismxCriticism, interpretation, etc. 0aLatin literaturexHistory and criticism. 0acanon. 0agenre system.  aFlavian Age.  acanon.  agenre system.1 aAugoustakis, Antony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaier, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalbo, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBessone, Federica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBonadeo, Alessia, econtributor.4ctb4